        "width": 1745,
        "url": "https://bitvision.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/cybersecurity/bot/welivesecurity.png",
        "proxy_url": "https://images-ext-1.discordapp.net/external/DW4UYn3rBilk3rFCoAPcIhUfGKTeKe80ELpX_-DlGjY/https/bitvision.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/cybersecurity/bot/welivesecurity.png",
        "placeholder_version": 1,
        "placeholder": "X1WBCYIkjgJ4iEiPePiIh3iHhYhwqJg=",
        "height": 247,
        "flags": 0
      },
      "description": "The Sednit espionage group, also known as the Sofacy group, APT28 or “Fancy Bear”, has been targeting various institutions for many years. We recently discovered a component the group employed to reach physically isolated computer networks -- “air-gapped” networks -- and exfiltrate sensitive files from them through removable drives.",
      "color": 44678
    },
    {
      "url": "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2014/11/12/korplug-military-targeted-attacks-afghanistan-tajikistan/",
      "type": "rich",
      "title": "Korplug military targeted attacks: Afghanistan & Tajikistan",
      "timestamp": "2014-11-12T15:17:17+00:00",
      "thumbnail": {
        "width": 1745,
        "url": "https://bitvision.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/cybersecurity/bot/welivesecurity.png",
        "proxy_url": "https://images-ext-1.discordapp.net/external/DW4UYn3rBilk3rFCoAPcIhUfGKTeKe80ELpX_-DlGjY/https/bitvision.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/cybersecurity/bot/welivesecurity.png",
        "placeholder_version": 1,
        "placeholder": "X1WBCYIkjgJ4iEiPePiIh3iHhYhwqJg=",
        "height": 247,
        "flags": 0
      },
      "description": "After taking a look at recent Korplug (PlugX) detections, we identified two larger scale campaigns employing this well-known Remote Access Trojan. This blog gives an overview of the first one",
      "color": 44678
    },
    {
      "url": "https://www.welivesecurity.com/2014/11/13/net-goes-open-source-cross-platform/",
      "type": "rich",
      "title": ".NET goes open source and cross-platform",
      "timestamp": "2014-11-13T16:43:08+00:00",
      "thumbnail": {
        "width": 1745,
        "url": "https://bitvision.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/cybersecurity/bot/welivesecurity.png",
        "proxy_url": "https://images-ext-1.discordapp.net/external/DW4UYn3rBilk3rFCoAPcIhUfGKTeKe80ELpX_-DlGjY/https/bitvision.s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/cybersecurity/bot/welivesecurity.png",
        "placeholder_version": 1,
        "placeholder": "X1WBCYIkjgJ4iEiPePiIh3iHhYhwqJg=",
        "height": 247,
        "flags": 0
      },
      "description": "Microsoft's .NET framework, which is used to build millions of websites and online applications, is taking further steps to go completely open-source, Microsoft has announced at the Connect() virtual development event. The company also stated its commitment to eventually ensure the free code runs on Mac OS and Linux too, Wired reports.",
